<p>The premise is this -- <br>
John and Kathy while chatting on Messenger, think of buying flight tickets. Kathy launches flight search using =flight search shortcut. This</p>]]></description><link>http://www.sasikiran.in/flight-search-partial-payment-using-messenger-bot/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">60762202-7e13-4e7f-b521-26dffc93e43a</guid><category><![CDATA[Design]]></category><dc:creator><![CDATA[Sasi Kiran Malladi]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 01 Jun 2016 16:56:54 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I'm not a big fan of chatbots. However, this UX concept designed by <a href="https://dribbble.com/isiluzum">Isil Uzum</a> with a Virgin Atlantic Messenger bot is very clever. </p>

<p>The premise is this -- <br>
John and Kathy while chatting on Messenger, think of buying flight tickets. Kathy launches flight search using =flight search shortcut. This triggers the flight bot, Virgin Atlantic in this case. Kathy gets to choose between Skyscanner and Kayak search engines for flights. She even makes Skyscanner as the default search engine. Then, she chooses a flight from JFK to SEA along with the start and end dates and makes it for 2 pax. Both John and Kathy get to fill in the passenger information and choose partial payment. Kathy only makes a partial payment. When both John and Kathy finish paying, their ticket confirmation pass is shown in the chat itself.</p>

<p>See the concept <a href="https://dribbble.com/shots/2749390-Messenger-Bots-Partial-payment-Concept">here</a>.</p>

<p>P.S. The GIF image is 7.5 MB and it may take some time to load the complete demo. </p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[My bucket list]]></title><description><![CDATA[<p>Everyone needs to have one. I will strike-off the items that I have completed. Also, this keeps a check on the progress I make year after the year.</p>

